  <h1>Cybersecurity Newsfeed</h1>
  <h2>📅 02/03/26</h2>

  <h2>🛡️ Vulnerabilities</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>"ClawJacked" WebSocket flaw in OpenClaw</strong>: A vulnerability in the OpenClaw AI platform allowed malicious websites to compromise local instances via WebSocket connections. By targeting the localhost gateway, attackers bypassed cross-origin policies to execute brute-force attacks on management passwords. OpenClaw v2026.2.26 addresses this by tightening security checks. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/clawjacked-attack-let-malicious-websites-hijack-openclaw-to-steal-data/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Critical RCE in Sangoma FreePBX (CVE-2025-64328)</strong>: Impacting over 900 instances, this flaw allows unauthenticated remote code execution via the web-based management interface. Attackers are scanning for exposed ports to deploy web shells for botnet integration or toll fraud. Urgent patches are available. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/188679/uncategorized/cve-2025-64328-exploitation-impacts-900-sangoma-freepbx-instances.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Unrestricted GCP API Keys exposed in public repos</strong>: Thousands of Google Cloud Platform API keys have been found in public repositories without "API restrictions." This allows unauthorized use of paid services like Translate and Maps. Google has accelerated automated scanning to notify affected developers. <a href="https://thehackernews.com/2026/02/thousands-of-public-google-cloud-api.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Gardyn Smart Garden critical API flaws</strong>: Insecure API implementations and hardcoded credentials in Gardyn indoor gardening systems could allow remote attackers to seize control of cameras and watering systems. While firmware updates are rolling out, manual updates are recommended due to lack of enforcement. <a href="https://www.securityweek.com/critical-flaws-exposed-gardyn-smart-gardens-to-remote-hacking/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>🎯 Adversaries</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Fake Gaming Utilities deliver Windows RAT</strong>: Microsoft identified a campaign distributing a Java-based Remote Access Trojan disguised as Xeno and Roblox tools. Using LOLBins like <code>cmstp.exe</code> and PowerShell, the malware modifies Windows Defender exclusions to ensure persistence and full system control. <a href="https://hackread.com/microsoft-fake-xeno-roblox-utilities-windows-rat/" target="_blank">More info</a> | <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/188639/malware/microsoft-warns-of-rat-delivered-through-trojanized-gaming-utilities.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>QuickLens extension targets Crypto via "ClickFix"</strong>: This malicious Chrome extension intercepts clipboard activity to swap wallet addresses and uses fake "system error" overlays to steal recovery seeds. Google has removed it from the Web Store, but manual audits of browser extensions are urged. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/quicklens-chrome-extension-steals-crypto-shows-clickfix-attack/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>"Steaelite RAT" enables double extortion</strong>: A new variant targeting corporate networks combines data exfiltration with ransomware. Steaelite uses sophisticated obfuscation to bypass EDR solutions and focuses on credential harvesting for lateral movement. <a href="https://www.theregister.com/2026/02/27/double_extortion_whammy_steaelite_rat/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Malicious Go module targets Crypto developers</strong>: A module mimicking popular libraries was found scanning developer environments for private keys and mnemonic phrases. This typosquatting attack highlights the need for verifying checksums and pinning dependencies in open-source repos. <a href="https://thehackernews.com/2026/02/malicious-go-crypto-module-steals.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>📈 Trends</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Aeternum botnet utilizes Polygon Blockchain</strong>: This botnet uses Polygon smart contracts to host C2 instructions, creating a decentralized "dead drop" that is nearly impossible to take down. Defenders are advised to monitor for unusual outbound RPC connections to blockchain endpoints. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/188627/mobile-2/aeternum-botnet-hides-commands-in-polygon-smart-contracts.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>APT37 bridges air-gapped networks via USB</strong>: North Korean threat actors are using infected USB drives to bridge physically isolated systems. The malware hides stolen documents in hidden partitions on the drive for later retrieval by the attackers. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/apt37-hackers-use-new-malware-to-breach-air-gapped-networks/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Resurge malware persists on Ivanti devices</strong>: CISA warned of "Resurge" malware that survives factory resets on Ivanti Connect Secure devices by embedding itself in non-volatile storage. Standard remediation is insufficient; manual integrity overhauls are recommended. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/cisa-warns-that-resurge-malware-can-be-dormant-on-ivanti-devices/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Cloaking techniques bypass Google Ad audits</strong>: A new malvertising campaign serves malicious content only to targeted users while showing benign ads to Google's reviewers. It uses IP filtering and fingerprinting to deliver infostealers to legitimate victims. <a href="https://hackread.com/hackers-1campaign-hide-malicious-ads-google-reviewers/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>💥 Breaches & Leaks</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>ShinyHunters leaks 6.1M Odido customer records</strong>: In the Netherlands' largest breach, attackers leaked data from Dutch telco Odido. Stolen info includes names, addresses, IBANs, and government IDs. Threat actors allege the dump contains plaintext passwords despite company denials. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/188709/data-breach/shinyhunters-leaked-the-full-odido-dataset.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Claude Code CLI abused in Mexican agency breach</strong>: Attackers exploited Anthropic’s CLI tool to exfiltrate 150GB of data from Mexican government agencies. The AI agent's autonomous capabilities were weaponized for rapid database discovery and internal mapping. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/188696/ai/claude-code-abused-to-steal-150gb-in-cyberattack-on-mexican-agencies.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Korean Tax Agency lapse leads to $48M Crypto theft</strong>: A digital wallet seed phrase was left in a publicly accessible document on a government server. Attackers discovered the file via dorking and drained funds intended for public infrastructure. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/48m-in-crypto-stolen-after-korean-tax-agency-exposes-wallet-seed/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>📚 Others</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pentagon designates Anthropic as critical provider</strong>: The U.S. DoD has officially partnered with Anthropic to integrate Claude-based models into national security frameworks, focusing on secure AI supply chains and threat intelligence. <a href="https://thehackernews.com/2026/02/pentagon-designates-anthropic-supply.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Law enforcement operation hits "The Com"</strong>: International authorities arrested 30 members of a notorious cybercrime ecosystem known for violent extortion, SIM swapping, and doxing. Millions in digital assets were seized. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/police-crackdown-on-the-com-cybercrime-gang-leads-to-30-arrests/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Research warns of third-party "Security Debt"</strong>: New studies highlight how delays in patching secondary applications and middleware create a massive attack surface, often exploited by automated scanners to gain initial network access. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/third-party-patching-and-the-business-footprint-we-all-share/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

